00:56:49.280 --> 00:56:51.570
like there's just no time left.

00:56:51.570 --> 00:56:52.520
Right?

00:56:52.520 --> 00:56:55.801
So how do you also work a career
plan and meet with mentors

00:56:55.801 --> 00:56:57.800
and read books on accounting
and all that stuff?

00:57:00.950 --> 00:57:03.610
So you have to be
hyper productive.

00:57:03.610 --> 00:57:07.070
And if you calculate
the number of hours

00:57:07.070 --> 00:57:09.410
that are already spoken
for in your life--

00:57:09.410 --> 00:57:12.564
you have sleep eight hours,
you have to sleep eight hours.

00:57:12.564 --> 00:57:14.480
Don't believe anyone
that tells you otherwise.

00:57:14.480 --> 00:57:15.606
You must sleep eight hours.

00:57:15.606 --> 00:57:17.063
You have to exercise
an hour a day.

00:57:17.063 --> 00:57:17.780
Have to.

00:57:17.780 --> 00:57:18.650
You really should.

00:57:18.650 --> 00:57:19.400
You have to bathe.

00:57:19.400 --> 00:57:21.020
You have to.

00:57:21.020 --> 00:57:22.070
Eat.

00:57:22.070 --> 00:57:24.320
And if you're ambitious,
you work 60 hours a week,

00:57:24.320 --> 00:57:26.270
which over seven
days averages out to,

00:57:26.270 --> 00:57:29.030
call it 8 hours, 8
and 1/2 hours a day.

00:57:29.030 --> 00:57:32.930
You add that all up, on an
average day, blending weekends

00:57:32.930 --> 00:57:36.110
and weekdays, you have five
hours of discretionary time

00:57:36.110 --> 00:57:37.070
every day.

00:57:37.070 --> 00:57:39.380
You have five hours to live.

00:57:39.380 --> 00:57:42.950
That's your time to
proactively decide

00:57:42.950 --> 00:57:45.320
how you are going to spend
it and what you're going

00:57:45.320 --> 00:57:47.720
to achieve with your life.

00:57:47.720 --> 00:57:50.180
The average American
spends five hours a day

00:57:50.180 --> 00:57:53.000
on social media and television.

00:57:53.000 --> 00:57:56.786
And then they all
say, I have no time.

00:57:56.786 --> 00:58:02.030
[CHIMES]

00:58:02.030 --> 00:58:04.470
And the bell tolls for you.

00:58:04.470 --> 00:58:07.850
If for five hours you
could be doing anything

00:58:07.850 --> 00:58:10.504
you want, anything you want.

00:58:10.504 --> 00:58:12.170
You could put more
hours into your work,

00:58:12.170 --> 00:58:14.540
so you don't work 60
hours, you work 70.

00:58:14.540 --> 00:58:17.510
There have been points in my
career where it's been 80.

00:58:17.510 --> 00:58:19.490
You decide when
that's appropriate.

00:58:19.490 --> 00:58:22.070
If you have kids, you
owe time to your kids.

00:58:22.070 --> 00:58:23.270
I love my children.

00:58:23.270 --> 00:58:24.950
Five hours every night's a lot.

00:58:24.950 --> 00:58:26.450
A lot.

00:58:26.450 --> 00:58:29.360
Two gets you there.

00:58:29.360 --> 00:58:31.610
You have time with friends,
you spend it proactively.

00:58:31.610 --> 00:58:33.776
You decide how you're going
invest those five hours.

00:58:33.776 --> 00:58:36.452
A portion of those five hours,
I invest in personal development

00:58:36.452 --> 00:58:37.160
almost every day.

00:58:37.160 --> 00:58:37.660
Right?

00:58:37.660 --> 00:58:38.240
Reading.

00:58:38.240 --> 00:58:39.720
There's a list of things
that I know I want to read,

00:58:39.720 --> 00:58:40.845
and I know I want to learn.

00:58:43.190 --> 00:58:45.320
Spending time with
people in the space

00:58:45.320 --> 00:58:47.130
who can give you
perspective, et cetera.

00:58:47.130 --> 00:58:49.100
A proactive investment
of that time.

00:58:49.100 --> 00:58:51.400
If you believe the
10,000-hour rule,

00:58:51.400 --> 00:58:53.990
with five hours every day,
in just a few years you,

00:58:53.990 --> 00:58:55.340
could also be a concert pianist.

00:58:55.340 --> 00:58:56.390
This is up to you.

00:58:56.390 --> 00:58:58.790
Five hours is a ton of time.

00:58:58.790 --> 00:59:01.600
But most of us don't
invest it proactively.

00:59:01.600 --> 00:59:02.600
It gets invested for us.

00:59:02.600 --> 00:59:03.222
We work.

00:59:03.222 --> 00:59:05.430
You get up, you're like,
shit, what am I doing today?

00:59:05.430 --> 00:59:05.602
All right.

00:59:05.602 --> 00:59:05.990
You scramble.

00:59:05.990 --> 00:59:07.460
You're like, I'm not going
to go to the gym now.

00:59:07.460 --> 00:59:08.251
I'll go after work.

00:59:08.251 --> 00:59:09.140
You work.

00:59:09.140 --> 00:59:11.110
Somebody bothers you,
and then it's 6:00

00:59:11.110 --> 00:59:12.920
and you've got to get home, and
then you didn't go to the gym.

00:59:12.920 --> 00:59:14.420
And you're home, and you
scramble with the kids,

00:59:14.420 --> 00:59:15.350
and then you're just beat.

00:59:15.350 --> 00:59:16.790
And you're like,
all right, I know

00:59:16.790 --> 00:59:20.377
I have some work to do but I'll
just like veg out for a minute.

00:59:20.377 --> 00:59:22.460
And next thing you know,
Netflix is saying to you,

00:59:22.460 --> 00:59:23.540
are you still there?

00:59:23.540 --> 00:59:25.340
Has that ever happened to you?

00:59:25.340 --> 00:59:26.940
Get a life.

00:59:26.940 --> 00:59:28.910
Of course I'm still here.

00:59:28.910 --> 00:59:31.010
I have found that
when I proactively

00:59:31.010 --> 00:59:34.520
say how I want to spend my time
and then put it in my calendar,

00:59:34.520 --> 00:59:36.130
that it works.

00:59:36.130 --> 00:59:38.994
And you calendar is this really
powerful operating system.

00:59:38.994 --> 00:59:40.910
You never miss a one-on-one
with your manager,

00:59:40.910 --> 00:59:43.490
because it's in your
calendar and you go.

00:59:43.490 --> 00:59:46.100
And yet, somehow we keep
not going to the gym.

00:59:46.100 --> 00:59:47.690
It's in my calendar.

00:59:47.690 --> 00:59:49.190
When I read is in my calendar.

00:59:49.190 --> 00:59:50.900
When I get in bed
is in my calendar.

00:59:50.900 --> 00:59:54.940
It's really weird.

00:59:54.940 --> 00:59:57.200
But it is really effective.

00:59:57.200 --> 00:59:59.990
There's this block
of time on Saturday

00:59:59.990 --> 01:00:03.517
that is my personal
time, not with my family,

01:00:03.517 --> 01:00:04.600
and it's not work related.

01:00:04.600 --> 01:00:09.140
It's investment in things
I want to learn, explore,

01:00:09.140 --> 01:00:09.890
or contribute.

01:00:09.890 --> 01:00:10.670
It's my time.

01:00:10.670 --> 01:00:13.310
It's 5:00 AM to about 10:00 AM.

01:00:13.310 --> 01:00:14.359
That's mine.

01:00:14.359 --> 01:00:15.900
There's this block
of time where it's

01:00:15.900 --> 01:00:18.560
going to be me with the kids,
and I will not check an email.

01:00:18.560 --> 01:00:20.322
I cannot be bothered.

01:00:20.322 --> 01:00:21.530
I'm going to be with my kids.

01:00:21.530 --> 01:00:23.030
It's dedicated time.

01:00:23.030 --> 01:00:25.610
And it's so much more powerful
when you wake up on Saturday,

01:00:25.610 --> 01:00:27.910
and you're like all right,
what are we going to do?

01:00:27.910 --> 01:00:33.980
So the most impassioned advice
I could give you on this topic

01:00:33.980 --> 01:00:38.090
is to proactively
schedule your five hours.

01:00:38.090 --> 01:00:41.840
I can also tell you, and
I said this in passing,

01:00:41.840 --> 01:00:44.510
but when you sleep, you really
are much more productive.

01:00:44.510 --> 01:00:46.070
They did an experiment.

01:00:46.070 --> 01:00:49.560
People were asked to sleep six
hours a night for two weeks,

01:00:49.560 --> 01:00:51.710
and they performed
cognitively and physically

01:00:51.710 --> 01:00:53.570
at the same level of
people who had pulled

01:00:53.570 --> 01:00:56.120
back-to-back all nighters.

01:00:56.120 --> 01:01:00.260
When you don't sleep,
you suck at everything.

01:01:00.260 --> 01:01:02.000
And we're all
ambitious, and so we're

01:01:02.000 --> 01:01:03.970
looking for an extra
hour and an extra hour.

01:01:03.970 --> 01:01:07.340
And you take it out of
sleep, and it's massively

01:01:07.340 --> 01:01:11.375
destructive to your
ability to be productive.

01:01:11.375 --> 01:01:12.250
So the way to do it--

01:01:12.250 --> 01:01:13.410
I said before, like
I literally have

01:01:13.410 --> 01:01:14.910
an alarm that goes
off that tells me

01:01:14.910 --> 01:01:16.160
it's time to get in bed.

01:01:16.160 --> 01:01:18.110
And I have to plug my
phone in, not by my bed,

01:01:18.110 --> 01:01:19.943
because if I bring my
phone to the bed, then

01:01:19.943 --> 01:01:22.580
I will lay in the bed with
the phone for another hour.

01:01:22.580 --> 01:01:24.530
The phone is actually
over by the door

01:01:24.530 --> 01:01:25.497
next to my gym clothes.

01:01:25.497 --> 01:01:27.830
And when the alarm goes off,
I get up, I get out of bed,

01:01:27.830 --> 01:01:29.360
I go, I grab the phone,
and I'm right there

01:01:29.360 --> 01:01:30.193
with my gym clothes.

01:01:30.193 --> 01:01:32.030
So I know I have to
go to the gym now.

01:01:32.030 --> 01:01:36.020
You can create these
barriers or these guardrails

01:01:36.020 --> 01:01:39.242
in your life that force you to
proactively and intelligently

01:01:39.242 --> 01:01:40.700
invest your time
in the things that

01:01:40.700 --> 01:01:44.720
maximize your productivity.

