MIKE STEIB: Oh, so this was, if
we had enough time, essentially

01:01:52.410 --> 01:01:54.499
quickly, the way to
manage your to-dos is

01:01:54.499 --> 01:01:56.790
to figure out what's the goal
you're trying to achieve?

01:01:56.790 --> 01:01:58.620
How much impact can
this action item have?

01:01:58.620 --> 01:01:59.650
How fast can you do it?

01:01:59.650 --> 01:02:01.140
And by when is it due?

01:02:01.140 --> 01:02:03.750
And we have a tendency
to go to a meeting

01:02:03.750 --> 01:02:06.630
and some to-dos come up, and
they go to the top of the list.

01:02:06.630 --> 01:02:09.480
And my advice is, you will never
do everything on your list.

01:02:09.480 --> 01:02:15.911
So always assess every to-do and
only do the high-leverage ones

01:02:15.911 --> 01:02:17.910
that you can-- first the
ones you can do quickly

01:02:17.910 --> 01:02:20.160
that are due soon and then
the high-leverage ones that

01:02:20.160 --> 01:02:21.120
take a long time.

01:02:21.120 --> 01:02:23.604
And match them to the amount
of time that you have.

01:02:23.604 --> 01:02:25.770
So you know how you have
15 minutes between meetings

01:02:25.770 --> 01:02:27.740
so you come back to your
desk and you open an email,

01:02:27.740 --> 01:02:29.040
and it's like a 20-page
PowerPoint you're

01:02:29.040 --> 01:02:29.804
supposed to read?

01:02:29.804 --> 01:02:31.470
And then you read
like four pages of it,

01:02:31.470 --> 01:02:33.210
but then the 15 minutes are up.

01:02:33.210 --> 01:02:34.890
So then you run to the meeting,
and then you come back,

01:02:34.890 --> 01:02:36.000
and you're like, OK,
let me go to my email.

01:02:36.000 --> 01:02:37.020
And you're like,
oh, this PowerPoint.

01:02:37.020 --> 01:02:37.520
Where was I?

01:02:37.520 --> 01:02:39.360
And you basically start over.

01:02:39.360 --> 01:02:42.330
Not matching the important
task to the amount of time

01:02:42.330 --> 01:02:44.080
with which you can
use to get it done

01:02:44.080 --> 01:02:46.730
is the way that most people
make themselves unproductive.

